As a result of the changes in the past decades – we have drawn up under point 1 – the Hungarian public educational system became a highly decentralised system, which relies on the shared responsibility of the central and local authorities. Together with the decentralisation of power there was a considerable increase in the decision-making capabilities of individual educational institutions in relation to planning their own programmes, and forming their inner relations and structures. It is not an overstatement that, under the present circumstances the quality of education and the satisfaction of those served by schools depends basically on the flexibility of individual schools, on the extent to which their offers harmonise with local requirements and last but not least, on the quality of the services offered by them. Such an enormous increase in institutional responsibility results in new tasks primarily for leaders; they have to face the greatest challenges. On the basis of these we can argue that in order to increase the effectiveness of the educational system and its functioning it is necessary to provide high quality pre-service and in-service training for both school leaders and those who wish to become one and for experts in different levels of educational policy making.
