Support of the local/institutional autonomy: The money goes from the government to the local authorities who must pass the 90% of the subsidy to the schools. The remained 10% serves local level aims: the retraining of the teachers and avoid them from the unemployment. Schools have the develop their own in-service training plan – in harmony with their pedagogical programme – and the teaching staff decide on it. The money can be used – either by the schools and their maintainers – for financing accredited in-service training programmes. The school head has to monitor the staff attendance at the training programmes.
The Act on Public Education of 1993 regulates the conditions of mandating the heads of educational institutions. It prescribes strict requirements in relation to the qualifications and the level of qualifications of leaders and it demands five years of professional experience, too. The original requirements on qualifications in the Act of 1993, however, did not include any expectations relating to educational management background (but it was corrected in 1996, see later). The candidates can usually – and they, in fact, normally do so – acquire the above described knowledge, skills and abilities necessary to professionally and successfully solving the tasks of a school manager in practice, that is only after taking over the responsibility of their new position. Within the framework of the Education Act school maintainers are free to decide on the person of school leaders, which can be seen as a natural right and situation accompanying ownership.
