The changes undergoing in the educational system can not be detached from the dramatic changes around their social political surroundings. There are (at least) two things we can mention here which are able to influence the education as sub-system seriously. The social-economical processes around the school are not predictable, and Hungary — as the other post-socialist countries — are characterised by economical depression. As a result of this the modernisation of the educational system has to be carried out in such a period when the system faces strong restriction. On the other hand the economy challenges the education with its new needs like informatics, foreign language knowledge, using computer, etc. The labour market needs – behind the knowledge – skills as flexibility, decision-making capacity, independence, etc., and these are becoming more and more important not only for the most qualified people and/or leaders. These challenges urge the educational system on adjustment and changes. 
The evaluation of the quality of the education from national to institutional level needs the clarification of such notions like effectiveness, efficacy, added values, etc. Behind the interpretation the evaluation presumes existence of suitable institutional background, well-prepared experts and adequate means. Hungary has considerable experiences in evaluating the students’ performances in different subjects. The country took part in the work of the IEA from the '70s and established a national monitoring system in second part of the '80s. It is due to the well developed educational researches the form of the national educational policy can rely on reliable analyses. These researches can serve not only the central decision making but also provide good basis for the school maintainers about the functioning of the system.
The new direction of the educational policy under the social–liberal coalition aimed at reducing the differences in the system, correcting the function of it to provide equal chance for the students as much as possible.
The profound and extremely speedy changes brought the in-service training of the teachers to great challenges. However the graduation of teacher education was challenged also, the in-service training – being more flexible – was easily able to react on the changes. The increasing ratio of the teachers' unemployment drew up the government's attention to this field as well. Finally overseas firms and private enterprises appeared on this field which generated an increasing competition between the possible trainees. The government considered the in-service training as one of the most important mean for modernising and making more efficient of the public education system.
The social political transformation — as in most Eastern European countries — has been accompanied by profound changes in the educational system as well. By the end of the '80s it become more or less clear and accepted how the Hungarian educational system should be renewed: increase the autonomy of schools, change the central curriculum into a core curriculum (making possible for schools to define — in the framework of the National Core Curriculum (NCC) — the content of the education, establishing a new examination system, etc. As a consequence of the political transformation new debate arose about the possible future of the Hungarian educational system. It was obvious that the basics of the future could be defined only by the legal power.
There are few professions in Hungary today that experienced greater changes and challenges than that of school managers. The work of head teachers has changed a lot in the past decade, its professional nature has become more and more articulate. This was strengthened by the Education Act of 1985, which – as we referred under point 1.1 – first in the history of Hungarian public education, declared the professional independence of schools and their staff. The enactment attached to the Act obliged the maintainers of public schools to choose head teachers through open competition. It also granted the faculty the right to put veto on decisions relating to mandating the head. (According to a resolution of the Jury of Constitution faculties lost this right in 1992.) Although the events mentioned above were ambiguous from several points of view – as we made an attempt to mirror them under point 1.2 –, in summary we can state that by the time political changes began school management developed into an independent profession, which is also proven by research results on management training.
Universities which wanted to have the right to run educational management courses formulated the requirements and made professional qualification a requirement of fulfilling leadership roles which help and speed up the process of professionalisation of the head teacher job. Offering management training in higher education and integrating these courses in such institutions mean the solution – as it did in other developed countries. At the same time it is indispensable from the point of view of high quality training that, unlike in traditional university courses, not only the academic sphere but practising experts take part in instruction too. Other fundamental issues are the practice-oriented nature of the training and the ongoing revision and development of the program and curriculum of the training. 
We suppose that the planned institutional framework can be built on the mutual advantages of the partners. Behind of the concrete professional aims and activities – developing and running high level course country and international level as well – we think it can serve to make even closer co-operation then we have, gives chance to take over the always existing cultural gaps, and so contribute to the idea of the European integration.
